Update: Call for elementary and middle school students to go out Friday morning. We did not want to send it too late Thursday night. High school student group announcements will follow, after final groups are updated within Harmony. We appreciate your patience!

Administrators are working to finalize the lists for which group each child will be a part of while we are in the hybrid model. We hoped to have the calls out earlier, but they are are still working on finalizing everything. As soon as they are ready, each family will receive a call letting them know which group they are in and which days they will be attending in person. We plan for the calls to go out this evening. If something happens and the calls cannot go out this evening, we will let parents know. Thank you for your understanding.

post_text:
CALLING ALL SUBSTITUTE TEACHERS:

The 2020-21 school year is quickly approaching and as you may expect, this year may look a bit different. To better prepare all of you, we are planning two training meetings, to be held on August 6 and 13. Attendance at one of these trainings will be MANDATORY for subs working within any PCSC school.

-Any substitute shown on our 2019-20 list was sent an email with details. If you did not receive an email, contact Lorice Chamberlain at 812-354-8731 or lchamberlain@pcsc.k12.in.us.

-Anyone who would like to begin subbing within our corporation, please contact Lorice (info above) to complete application paperwork and receive training details.

-Anyone on the 2019-20 list who no longer wishes to sub, please contact Lorice to be removed from our contact sheets.

Thank you for your dedication to our students. We look forward to seeing you soon!

Pike Central High School
July 23 at 9:19 AM ¬∑

On Monday, July 27, from 3-5 p.m. in the front parking lot of PCHS

Any student who attended prom can pick up
* A prom glass
* Any prom photos they ordered.

2020 graduates can pick up
* Any graduation photos they ordered
* A copy of the virtual graduation DVD
* Students who want to order photos need to view prices on the attached order form, and contact Harting‚Äôs Studios (812) 354-8037 or email jeffharting@aol.com

Parents/guardians can pick up items for their child if the student is not available.

Students can pick up items for another student IF
1. They were a prom guest from another school, a PC graduate, or an underclassman
2. Can show permission from the other student, via text message.

Items not picked up on July 27 will be available in the HS office, once school is back in session.

The PCSC Food Service will be ending distributions for the 2020 Closure/Summer after the scheduled pick-ups on Wednesday, July 8th. Our wonderful cafeteria staff need time to plan and organize for the upcoming school year, which will begin 4 short weeks after that last date. We hope they will also have a little time to rest after working tirelessly to serve our community‚Äôs children throughout these trying times. We cannot thank them enough for their efforts and dedication!

The opportunity below is open to EVERYONE, and we encourage you to participate. Also, if you‚Äôre struggling with food insecurity or hunger, remember our generous local food pantry is operating and available to help.

Thank you!

End-of-year updates (5/19/20):

Report cards will be mailed home June 2. This allows time for any remaining packets to be sanitized, and for teachers to prepare all grades. No packets will be accepted after the final due date of May 20.

PES & WES Student pick-up of items will be on May 27 from 2:00 - 6:00 pm and May 28 from 10:00 am - 2:00 pm. All items must be picked up by June 3 before school offices close for the summer.

PCHS & PCMS Locker Clean-outs will be on May 27 from 8:30 am - 3:30 pm and May 28 from 12:00 pm to 6:00 pm

Chromebook Returns will be on May 27 from 8:00 am - 6:00 pm and May 28 from 8:00 am - 4:00 pm.
‚ÄîGrades 9-11 will return devices and chargers during HS locker clean outs, to the D-Wing Tech Dept. office.
‚ÄîGrades K-8 Borrowed devices will be returned to the tech department at the HS, from the outside entrance (burgundy door to the left of the entrance marked D102).

You are welcome to call your child‚Äôs school office with questions. Thank you for your patience and outstanding cooperation with all processes thus far. It is truly appreciated!

FOOD SERVICE UPDATE 5/18/20

PCSC will continue to serve meals on Monday, Wednesday and Friday through May 29, 2020, with the exception of Memorial Day (May 25). Food will be available for pick-up at all distribution sites.

PCSC will continue to serve meals on Wednesdays only from June 3 to July 8, 2020. Food will be available from 11:00 am to 12:30 pm at all distribution sites on Wednesdays.

Information will be posted later regarding service plans for late July to August.

We will continue as planned for the next two weeks:

eLearning March 30-April 3

We will continue to provide students with meals through May 1st.

The PCSC administrative team will be meeting to explore all available options for April 6-May 1, and will share additional information as soon as decisions have been reached.

Thank you and stay safe.

Pike County School Corporation will be closed from March 16 to April 3. Students will be provided eLearning assignments for March 16 to March 20, and for March 30 to April 3. In observance of Spring Break, no assignments will be posted for the week of March 23 to March 27. All students should take home textbooks, notebooks, school supplies, electronic devices or any personal items that may be needed during the next 3 weeks.

All staff members need to report to work on Monday, March 16 at their regular time. Meetings will be held to review any final plans or preparations for the extended closure. Additional information regarding the provision of school breakfast and lunch, arrangements for picking up medicine, any special accommodations, or any other details will be provided to families by Monday, March 16 through social media and school reach calls.

Please join us in our 6th annual fundraising efforts for Riley Hospital for Children! With your help, we can make a difference in the lives of the over 300,000 children who visit Riley each year-- including many that come from our own community. Not only are you helping the children who are treated at Riley but you are also supporting the endeavors of the 100+ Pike Central students who participate in our dance marathon each year. Everything we do at the PCDM is FTK!

(FTK stand for For the Kids, just in case anyone was wondering! :)

post_text:
Early this morning, one of our teachers passed away. Mr. Ivan Mason was in his 40th year of teaching for the Pike County School Corporation. Most of his teaching career was completed at Winslow Elementary before transferring to Pike Central Middle School where he has taught 6th grade Social Studies for the past few years. He was a familiar face at our sporting events and encouraged all students to do and be their best at all times. Staff and students learned of the loss today at school, but I wanted to let the families of our district know as well.
At this time, Pike County School Corporation will be closed on Monday, Feb 24. Students will be provided additional information tomorrow regarding assignments to completed on that day. Visitation for Mr. Mason will be held at the gym at Pike Central on Sunday, Feb 23, from 3:00 to 8:00 pm (Pike Co time) and on Monday, Feb 24, at Corn Colvin Funeral Home from 11:00 am until the time of service at 12:00 pm. Please keep Mr. Mason‚Äôs family and friends in your thoughts and prayers during this difficult time.

The Love, Jordan premiere was an incredible success! I‚Äôm happy to say that I held a role in bringing this story to life. What started out as an idea became an emotional project that has sparked conversation and hope for change. I‚Äôve already heard several amazing stories about how this premiere, and the conversations that sparked from it, have actually helped people! This topic is something that hits me close to the chest and I‚Äôm beyond excited that it made such an impact. It‚Äôs one thing to say we make content; it‚Äôs another to say we make content for change.

Photo by Mick Hetman Photography

post_text:
The Key Club is hosting a flag retirement ceremony this Saturday, April 20 at 1 p.m. in the PCHS parking lot. The public is invited to attend this special ceremony. Bleachers will be available but you may also bring your own lawn chairs. If you have a flag that is worn and needs to be properly retired, please bring it with you or send it to Amanda Stevens or Cassi Craig by this Thursday, April 18. You may also retire a flag in honor of a loved one who has served our country if you wish.

The local VFW is assisting with the ceremony. There will be a few guest speakers and musicians present, from the Key Club as well as the community. This part of the ceremony will last 30 minutes or less, with the flag retirement continuing past that time for approximately an hour.

If you have any questions please email Amanda Stevens (astevens@pcsc.k12.in.us) or Cassi Craig (ccraig@pcsc.k12.in.us).

post_text: PCSC alumni making us proud! Congratulations and good luck in the future.
shared_text:
Dylan Query is with Jacob Stieneker and 4 others at Ball State University.
April 10, 2019 at 12:22 AM ¬∑ Muncie, IN ¬∑

I write this with a happy and proud heart... As I near graduation, RETNE has become my swan song for my time at Ball State University. What makes me even more proud is that I had a few of my closest friends next to me the whole time for this project.

RETNE won Best Cinematography, Best Editing, and Best Color Grade at Ball State's Frog Baby Film Festival.

Thanks guys for creating more meaning and more purpose to my time here. Here's to all the projects to come... üç∑üçø

And also a big special thanks to Mick Hetman Photography for all the incredible photos throughout the night. I'll be posting more of them in the future!

post_text: Great job and good luck
shared_text:
Pike Central High School
March 19, 2019 at 12:48 PM ¬∑

Pike Central High School's Business Professionals of America chapter had a successful trip to the 2019 State Conference in Indianapolis, March 10-12. Seven of the club's students earned the chance to attend while competing at the Regional Conference back in January. The students and their events include: Andrew Clark in Human Resource Management, Emily Hill in Medical Office, Jenna Horrall in Economic Research, Sean Keith in Medical Office, Sydney Keith in Medical Office and Economic Research, Madison Warner in Intermediate Word Processing and Office Systems, and Kyle Williams in Legal Office and Business Law and Ethics.

After everyone completed their rigorous events, two students, Sydney Keith and Kyle Williams advanced to Nationals, which will be held in Anaheim, California this year. They will compete at the national level May 1-5, representing Pike County and Indiana BPA among the top students in the nation. Sydney and Kyle will enjoy many leadership and sightseeing opportunities while attending the conference.
